:"1158–Deceased","1174–Male":"1174–Deceased","1178–Male":"1178–Deceased","1140–Female":"1140–Deceased","1190–1220":"1190–1220","1126–1196":"1126–1196","0112–1186":"0112–1186","1190":"1190","Abt 1140/1160":"from 8 January 1140 to 7 January 1161","1220":"1220","1154":"1154","1176":"1176","1186":"1186","1196":"1196","1174":"1174","1152":"1152","1140":"1140","1149":"1149","1126":"1126","0112":"0112","1158":"1158","1178":"1178","Abt 1180":"about 1180","Abt 1190":"about 1190",", of Stafford, England":"Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Corbin Hall, Stafford, England":"Corbins Hall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Corbin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and English: nickname meaning ‘little crow, raven’, possibly applied to a black haired man, from Old French, Middle English <i>corbin</i>, a diminutive of <i>corb</i> ‘raven’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>corbin</i>, <i>corfbin</i> ‘crow, raven’).","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of the places in Calvados and Orne, France, named Corbon.","Irish: variant of   Corban  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Carbin","meanings":["Swedish: soldier's name, from Swedish <i>karbin</i> ‘carbine’, a type of short rifle or musket used by cavalry.","Cornish: hypercorrect backformation from Cornish <i>carr-bons</i> ‘causeway’, or a habitational name from Carbis in Lelant (Cornwall), of the same derivation.","English: variant of   Corbin  ."]},{"name":"Corvin","meanings":["English (Durham): possibly a variant of   Corbin  .","Altered form of Scottish, Irish or English   Colvin  .","Possibly also an Americanized form of Dutch <b>Korving</b> (mainly The Hague): from the personal name <i>Korving</i>, from <i>Corvinus</i>, from Latin <i>corvus</i> ‘raven’."]},{"name":"Corban","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Corbáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Corbán</i>’ or <b>Ó Coirbín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Coirbín</i>’, both possibly from an occupational name based on <i>corb</i> ‘chariot’. Both names have also been Anglicized as   Corbett  .","Irish: alternatively, a variant of <b>Currivan</b>, from <b>Ó Coirbheáin</b>, itself a variant of   Corban   (pronounced with three syllables in Irish).","Romanian: nickname derived from <i>corb</i> ‘crow’, with the augmentative suffix <i>-an</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Corbin was born from 8 January 1140 to 7 January 1161, in Corbins Hall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert Corbin IV, was 35 and his mother, Baroness Tegen, was 1049. He married Mrs. William Corbin about 1180, in Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1140/1160–":"8. jaanuar 1140 kuni 7. jaanuar 1161–Surnud","1149–1176":"1149–1176","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1152–Male":"1152–Surnud","1154–Female":"1154–Surnud","1158–Female":"1158–Surnud","1174–Male":"1174–Surnud","1178–Male":"1178–Surnud","1140–Female":"1140–Surnud","1190–1220":"1190–1220","1126–1196":"1126–1196","0112–1186":"0112–1186","1190":"1190","Abt 1140/1160":"8. jaanuar 1140 kuni 7. jaanuar 1161","1220":"1220","1154":"1154","1176":"1176","1186":"1186","1196":"1196","1174"